stylometry: @Risk works by running a model with a risk function such as risksimtable.  It is helpful because you can run the model with several inputs at one time and compare all of the results to determine the maximum profit with the least amount of risk.  When you run the simulation with 5 different inputs, all 5 inputs are solved and they show the standard deviation, the minimum, and the maximum profits.  Based on the standard deviation and the maximum and minimum profits you can determine which input is the best available choice.  An input may have the highest maximum profit, but the standard deviation may sway the choice because it may also be the riskiest choice with the lowest minimum profit.
